# How to Access Your Website on Any Device

When you run `python manage.py runserver 8080`, the website is only accessible on your **local computer**. 
To make it accessible from any device (like a mobile phone or another laptop), you have two main options:

---

## Option 1: Temporary Public Link (Quick & Easy)
This method is perfect if you just want to test your website on a mobile phone right now. 
**Note:** The link will stop working as soon as you turn off your computer or close the terminal.

### Method A: Localhost Tunnel (No Installation Required)
Open a new terminal in VS Code (`Terminal -> New Terminal`) and run this exact command:
```bash
ssh -R 80:localhost:8080 nokey@localhost.run
```
*Wait a few seconds, and it will print a web link (e.g., `https://something.lhr.life`). You can open that link on any device in the world to see your live site.*

### Method B: Using Ngrok
If you want something more robust for testing:
1. Download and install [Ngrok](https://ngrok.com/).
2. Run this command in a new terminal:
```bash
ngrok http 8080
```
*Ngrok will provide a "Forwarding URL" that you can share with anyone.*

---

## Option 2: Truly Permanent Link (Cloud Hosting)
If you want a **permanent link** that works 24/7 even when your laptop is turned off, you need to deploy your Django project to a cloud hosting provider.

Since this is a Python/Django project, the easiest free options are:
1. **PythonAnywhere** (Easiest for quick Django deployments)
2. **Render.com** (Modern, but requires setting up PostgreSQL and GitHub)

### Quick Guide for PythonAnywhere:
1. Go to [PythonAnywhere](https://www.pythonanywhere.com/) and create a free beginner account.
2. Upload your project files (`project frank` folder).
3. Open a bash console on PythonAnywhere and install dependencies:
   ```bash
   pip install django pandas scikit-learn
   ```
4. Configure the Web tab to point to your [manage.py](file:///c:/Users/ELCOT/Downloads/project%20frank/manage.py) and WSGI file.

*If you would like me to help you deploy the website permanently to PythonAnywhere or Render, just let me know and we can go through the steps together!*
